```

Base64 encoding will convert your long string into a shorter string, and it's safe to use in URLs. However, keep in mind that Base64 encoding will increase the size of your string by approximately 33%.

Also, remember that some characters are not allowed in URLs, so if your original string contains such characters, they will be encoded as %XX where XX is the hexadecimal representation of the character. Base64 encoding will handle these characters correctly.

Lastly, it's important to note that Base64 encoding is not secure by itself, but it's a good choice for data that doesn't need to be kept secret. If you need to encode sensitive data, consider using URL-safe Base64 encoding (which replaces unsafe characters) or a more secure method like URL-safe Base64 with a secret key.

